          cronedit - update crontab file

     SSSSYYYYNNNNOOOOPPPPSSSSIIIISSSS
          ccccrrrroooonnnneeeeddddiiiitttt

     DDDDEEEESSSSCCCCRRRRIIIIPPPPTTTTIIIIOOOONNNN
          The _c_r_o_n_e_d_i_t program enables the user to more easily manage
          crontab files.  It helps prevent situations where you have
          edited a file to update the crontab schedule, but then
          forget to submit the file to _c_r_o_n_t_a_b. The edited crontab
          file, ._c_r_o_n_t_a_b, will be kept in the $HOME directory, unless
          specified otherwise by the CRONTAB environment variable.

          It starts by getting the current crontab file (using _c_r_o_n_t_a_b
          -_l) if there is one, and then it puts the user into the
          editor to make whatever changes are desired.  After exiting
          the editor, the user is prompted as to whether the edited
          file should be submitted to _c_r_o_n_t_a_b. If the answer is "yes,"
          the edited file is submitted to _c_r_o_n_t_a_b. Either way, the
          edited crontab file is left in $HOME/.crontab or whatever is
          designated by CRONTAB.  This is handy in case you get moved
          to another machine, because you have a file all ready to
          submit to crontab on your new machine.

          Virtually the same function is provided on SunOS machines by
          executing _c_r_o_n_t_a_b -_e, but _c_r_o_n_e_d_i_t also saves the edited
          file for you.

